Use Codex internal web search for search queries. Do not use the configured browser or Playwright MCP to open public search-engine result pages. Use the configured browser only to open, interact with, and verify target source pages selected from internal search results, site navigation, saved evidence, or prompt context. All target source-page and source-data loading must go through the configured browser. Do not use non-browser loading mechanisms for target source data; direct HTTP, curl, requests, wget, and Python scraping are examples of forbidden replacements, not an exhaustive list.

Use browser_evaluate with pure browser JavaScript for page data extraction. The injected page JavaScript may read DOM, window, document, links, tables, visible text, and browser-visible state, then return serializable data. It must not use Node.js APIs or module systems: require, dynamic import, node: modules, fs, path, process, Buffer, and local filesystem access are forbidden in browser JavaScript. Do not use browser_run_code_unsafe.

Before clicking a page target, close or answer browser-visible cookie banners, drawers, and overlays that intercept pointer events, then retry the target action. When a selector or text locator matches multiple elements, use the browser snapshot to choose a scoped unique target instead of repeating the broad locator. Retry transient browser navigation failures such as ERR_NETWORK_CHANGED through the same configured browser before treating the source as unavailable.
